covered: Valid Request: Valid updates tested for minimal payloads (TC01) and full payloads (TC02), ensuring correct update behavior.
Null handling and treatNullAsReset: TC03 and TC04 cover null-valued fields and reset behavior based on treatNullAsReset.
Authorization: Tests for missing X-Killbill-CreatedBy header (TC05) and unauthorized access (TC09) validate access control for PUT.
Validation: Invalid accountId format (TC06), invalid account data (TC07, TC21), and empty request body (TC11) cover input validation and error handling.
Resource existence: Non-existent account (TC08) validates behavior when updating a non-existent resource.
Edge cases: Extra fields (TC10) and extra query parameters (TC22) are handled gracefully.
Headers usage: The tests consistently require X-Killbill-CreatedBy header; additional headers in TC02 (Reason/Comment) are validated in test scenarios.
Error handling: System error scenario (TC12) demonstrates 500 responses for server errors.
Performance and robustness: Large payload (TC13) and slow network (TC14) test behavior under heavy payload and latency while aiming for acceptable response times.
Integration: Dependent-service propagation is tested in TC16 and regression handling in TC15 ensures field-level integrity.
Partial update: Only provided fields are updated (TC19).
Range checks: Minimum and maximum values for fields (TC20) are tested.
Security: Malicious input handling (TC18) validates input sanitization.
Data integrity: Regression test TC15 ensures updating one field does not overwrite others.
gaps: 403 Forbidden (insufficient privileges) is not explicitly tested.
Caching behavior (ETag / Cache-Control) is not tested.
Rate limiting / throttling behavior is not explicitly tested.
Auditing/logging validation is not explicitly tested.
recommendations: Add a 403 Forbidden test to cover insufficient privileges during update.
Add tests validating caching headers (ETag and Cache-Control) to ensure proper caching behavior.
Introduce rate-limiting tests to verify system behavior under high request volume and throttling.
Add tests for auditing/logging events to verify that updates are properly recorded.
